---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import { getContactLinks, siteConfig } from "../site";

const contactLinks = getContactLinks();
const { about, location, role } = siteConfig.profile;
---

<BaseLayout
  title="About"
  description="Short context around the site, the work, and the writing cadence."
>
  <section class="page-intro">
    <p class="eyebrow">About</p>
    <h1 class="page-title">{role}</h1>

    <p class="page-copy">{about}</p>

    <p class="page-copy">
      The current material is built mostly from repo history: ADRs, planning
      notes, sprint snapshots, runbooks, and the occasional incident fix that
      says more than a polished README ever will.
    </p>

    <p class="page-copy">
      The recurring themes are plain enough: declarative infrastructure,
      boundaries that can survive iteration, and a preference for keeping tools
      in the role they are actually good at. Home Assistant stays an edge
      runtime. Flux stays the reconciler. A case study only gets published once
      the repo has enough evidence to support one.
    </p>

    {location ? <p class="page-copy">Location: {location}</p> : null}

    {
      contactLinks.length > 0 ? (
        <ul class="link-row" aria-label="External links">
          {contactLinks.map((link) => (
            <li>
              <a class="link-chip" href={link.href} rel="noreferrer">
                {link.label}
              </a>
            </li>
          ))}
        </ul>
      ) : (
        <p class="publication-note">
          GitHub, LinkedIn, and email are supported by the site config and only
          render once real values are set.
        </p>
      )
    }
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
